snippet.textDisplay: two Intel Xeon E5-2667 v2 still perform worse than AMD Ryzen 3800X even when utilized fully.  For example, in PassMark they get 22,729 vs 24,508 for a single Ryzen 3800X.  Not to mention, they are rated at a 130W TDP each.  that is 260W vs 105W for Ryzen's 3800X.  This would contribute to how loud and hot the system is, as well as, the amount of electricity used by the system. I remember few years back I got a Dell Precision Desktop which had similar specifications with two Intel Xeon CPU's from a University Disposal Center.  It just doesn't run as well as the newer system.  When I bought the system DDR3 was common on desktops but the Precision had DDR2 memory, which was a big bottleneck.  Also, the SATA ports were not as fast as what was commonly used when I purchased the system (I believe the desktop had SATA 1 or 2).  Also, PCI-E was at first gen, I think.  All of these contribute to the performance of the PC, and in my opinion, it is very noticeable.

snippet.textDisplay:
For audio post, I still run a dual 8 core z620 workstation with 128gb of ram and I'm not planning to upgrade. Multitrack audio runs extremely well on many cores and you can still do additional tasks like video conversion or exports in the background. At home, I still rock my 2600k @4.7ghz and I just ordered a Ryzen 3800x to replace it. However, I do not expect to have my socks blown off.
Today's real performance gains come through software optimization. CPU wise, nothing earth-shattering happened within the last 9 years. The 3800x isn't even twice as fast per core than the 2600k is. Leaps like going to 486DX, Core2 or Sandy Bridge just don't happen anymore.
